---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHero from '../../components/PageHero.astro';
import CompareTable from '../../components/CompareTable.astro';

const rows = [
  {
    dimension: 'Where it runs',
    cha: 'In your cluster — operator + CronJob + Deployment',
    competitor: 'Causely SaaS with an in-cluster ingestor agent',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'Closed-loop remediation',
    cha: 'Yes — 5 policy-bounded fixers + AI-tier proposals on operator approval',
    competitor: 'Causal RCA + recommendation; remediation is an external system call (PagerDuty, ticket, etc.)',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'Method',
    cha: 'Probes + analyzers + LLM agent reasoning over closed-enum tools',
    competitor: 'Causal graph over telemetry; identifies the upstream root cause node',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'LLM provider',
    cha: 'Bring-your-own — any OpenAI-compatible endpoint',
    competitor: 'Vendor-managed; causal model is proprietary',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'Pricing model',
    cha: 'Flat per-cluster (Open Core free / AI SRE Team / Enterprise)',
    competitor: 'Contact-sales SaaS pricing',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'Air-gap / sovereign',
    cha: 'Yes — OSS engine and CHA-com both run entirely in-cluster',
    competitor: 'No — telemetry flows to Causely SaaS for graph inference',
  },
  {
    dimension: 'Open source',
    cha: 'Apache-2.0 engine; commercial AI SRE tier',
    competitor: 'Proprietary',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CHA vs. Causely"
  description="Causely uses a causal-AI graph to find root causes across observability telemetry but doesn't remediate. CHA probes the cluster, proposes specific fixes inside operator policy, and executes them with one click."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Compare &middot; Causely"
    title="CHA vs. Causely"
    subtitle="Causely is a causal-AI root-cause tool. CHA is an autonomous SRE agent that closes the loop — detect, propose, approve, execute, re-verify. Different value at different layers; if you want both, the integration is a webhook."
  />

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20">
    <CompareTable competitorName="Causely" rows={rows} />

    <div class="mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200/80 bg-zinc-50/60 p-8 dark:border-zinc-800/80 dark:bg-zinc-950/40">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-50">
        The structural difference.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Causely's strength is causal inference over telemetry &mdash; given a
        symptom in one service, identify which upstream service or
        infrastructure component is the actual cause. That's a useful primitive
        for noisy multi-service incidents, and Causely does it well.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        But finding the root cause is one step in a five-step loop &mdash;
        detect, root-cause, propose, approve, execute, re-verify. Causely sells
        the second step. The remaining steps still need either an SRE to act
        manually or another tool wired in. The telemetry is also outbound to
        their SaaS for the causal graph computation.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        CHA covers all five steps in one in-cluster runtime: probes detect the
        drift, the LLM Investigator agent reasons about it, the T1 fix
        proposer (or T2 planner) proposes specific action_kinds within
        operator policy, the operator clicks once, the runtime executes, and
        the watcher re-verifies. If you want the best of both, point Causely's
        webhook at the CHA approval-server and you have a complete pipeline.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
